@node Introduction
@chapter Introduction

@cindex T-Lisp
@cindex introduction

T-Lisp (tmax Lisp) is a Lisp-1 dialect embedded in the tmax terminal text editor.
It provides all editor extensibility through a comprehensive API.

@itemize @bullet
@item @strong{Lisp-1 dialect} --- variables and functions share the same namespace
@item @strong{Lexical scoping} --- variables are scoped to their defining block
@item @strong{Tail-call optimization} --- recursive calls in tail position use constant stack
@item @strong{Macro system} --- full quasiquote support for metaprogramming
@item @strong{200+ editor API functions} --- complete control over the editor
@item @strong{Testing framework} --- built-in test definitions and assertions
@end itemize

@node Lexical Structure
@chapter Lexical Structure

@cindex lexical structure
@cindex comments
@cindex identifiers

@section Comments

Comments begin with @code{;} and extend to end of line:

@example
;; This is a comment
(+ 1 2) ; inline comment
@end example

@section Identifiers

Identifiers may contain letters, digits, and: @code{-}, @code{_}, @code{?}, @code{!}, @code{+}, @code{*}, @code{/}, @code{<}, @code{>}, @code{=}

@example
x  my-variable  buffer-insert  nil?  set!  +  <=
@end example

@section String Literals

Double-quoted with escape sequences:

@example
"hello world"
"Line 1\nLine 2"
"Say \"hello\""
@end example

@section Number Literals

@example
42    -17    3.14    -2.5
@end example

@section Special Tokens

@table @code
@item ( )
Parentheses delimit lists and function calls
@item '
Quote --- shorthand for @code{(quote ...)}
@item `
Quasiquote --- template quotation
@item ,
Unquote --- evaluate within quasiquote
@item @code{,@@}
Unquote-splice --- splice list elements within quasiquote
@end table

@node Data Types
@chapter Data Types

@cindex data types

@table @code
@item Numbers
Integers and floating-point: @code{42}, @code{-17}, @code{3.14}

@item Strings
Text in double quotes: @code{"hello"}, @code{"file.txt"}

@item Symbols
Identifiers that name variables: @code{x}, @code{buffer-insert}

@item Lists
Ordered collections: @code{'(1 2 3)}, @code{(list 1 2 3)}

@item Booleans
@code{#t} (true), @code{#f} (false)

@item Nil
Empty list / false: @code{nil} or @code{'()}

@item Hash Maps
Key-value stores: @code{(hashmap "key" "value")}

@item Functions
Created with @code{lambda} or @code{defun}

@item Macros
Created with @code{defmacro}
@end table

@node Evaluation
@chapter Evaluation

@cindex evaluation

@itemize @bullet
@item @strong{Self-evaluating}: numbers, strings, booleans, nil evaluate to themselves
@item @strong{Symbols}: looked up in the current environment chain
@item @strong{Lists}: first element is the function, remaining elements are evaluated as arguments
@item @strong{Special forms}: @code{if}, @code{let}, @code{lambda}, etc.---evaluated with custom rules
@end itemize

@example
(+ 1 2 3)         ; function call => 6
(if (> x 0) x 0)  ; special form
(let ((x 10)) x)   ; special form => 10
@end example

@node Special Forms
@chapter Special Forms

@cindex special forms

@deffn Special Form quote expr
Return @var{expr} without evaluating it.
@example
(quote x)    ; => x
'(1 2 3)     ; => (1 2 3)
@end example
@end deffn

@deffn Special Form if condition then-expr else-expr
Evaluate @var{condition}. If truthy, evaluate and return @var{then-expr}; otherwise evaluate and return @var{else-expr}.
@example
(if (> 3 2) "yes" "no")  ; => "yes"
@end example
@end deffn

@deffn Special Form let bindings body...
Create local variable bindings. @var{bindings} is a list of @code{(name value)} pairs.
@example
(let ((x 10) (y 20))
  (+ x y))  ; => 30
@end example
@end deffn

@deffn Special Form lambda params docstring? body...
Create an anonymous function. Optional @var{docstring} after @var{params}.
@example
(lambda (x) (* x x))
(funcall (lambda (x y) (+ x y)) 3 4)  ; => 7
@end example
@end deffn

@deffn Special Form defun name params docstring? body...
Define a named function in the current environment.
@example
(defun square (x)
  (* x x))
(square 5)  ; => 25
@end example
@end deffn

@deffn Special Form defmacro name params body...
Define a macro. The body is evaluated at expansion time, not call time.
@example
(defmacro when (condition . body)
  `(if ,condition (progn ,@@body)))
@end example
@end deffn

@deffn Special Form progn expr...
Evaluate each expression in sequence. Return the value of the last.
@example
(progn
  (buffer-insert "Hello")
  (cursor-move 0 0))
@end example
@end deffn

@deffn Special Form cond clause...
Multi-way conditional. Each clause is @code{(condition expr)}. Use @code{t} as condition for else.
@example
(cond
  ((< x 0) "negative")
  ((= x 0) "zero")
  (t "positive"))
@end example
@end deffn

@deffn Special Form defvar name value
Define a variable in the global environment.
@example
(defvar tab-width 4)
@end example
@end deffn

@deffn Special Form set! name value
Set an existing variable's value.
@example
(set! tab-width 2)
@end example
@end deffn

@node Quasiquote System
@chapter Quasiquote System

@cindex quasiquote
@cindex unquote
@cindex macro

@deffn Special Form quasiquote expr @code{`}
Template quotation --- like @code{quote} but allows selective evaluation.
@example
`(a b c)              ; => (a b c)
@end example
@end deffn

@deffn Special Form unquote expr @code{,}
Evaluate @var{expr} within a quasiquote.
@example
(let ((x 42))
  `(the answer is ,x))  ; => (the answer is 42)
@end example
@end deffn

@deffn Special Form unquote-splicing expr @code{,@@}
Splice list elements into the enclosing quasiquote.
@example
(let ((nums '(1 2 3)))
  `(before ,@@nums after))  ; => (before 1 2 3 after)
@end example
@end deffn

@node Standard Library
@chapter Standard Library

@cindex standard library

@section Arithmetic

@deffn Function + numbers...
Addition. With no arguments returns 0.
@example
(+)          ; => 0
(+ 5)        ; => 5
(+ 1 2 3)    ; => 6
@end example
@end deffn

@deffn Function - numbers...
Subtraction. With one argument, negation.
@example
(- 5)        ; => -5
(- 10 3)     ; => 7
(- 20 5 2)   ; => 13
@end example
@end deffn

@deffn Function * numbers...
Multiplication. With no arguments returns 1.
@example
(*)          ; => 1
(* 3 4)      ; => 12
@end example
@end deffn

@deffn Function / numbers...
Division. With one argument, reciprocal.
@example
(/ 2)        ; => 0.5
(/ 10 2)     ; => 5
@end example
@end deffn

@deffn Function mod dividend divisor
Modulo operation.
@example
(mod 7 3)    ; => 1
@end example
@end deffn

@deffn Function abs number
Absolute value.
@example
(abs -5)     ; => 5
@end example
@end deffn

@deffn Function min numbers...
Minimum of arguments.
@example
(min 3 1 4 1 5)  ; => 1
@end example
@end deffn

@deffn Function max numbers...
Maximum of arguments.
@example
(max 3 1 4 1 5)  ; => 5
@end example
@end deffn

@deffn Function sqrt number
Square root.
@example
(sqrt 16)    ; => 4
@end example
@end deffn

@deffn Function expt base exponent
Exponentiation.
@example
(expt 2 10)  ; => 1024
@end example
@end deffn

@deffn Function floor number
Round down to integer.
@end deffn

@deffn Function ceiling number
Round up to integer.
@end deffn

@deffn Function round number
Round to nearest integer.
@end deffn

