@node Macro System
@chapter Macro System

@cindex macros
@cindex defmacro

Macros transform code at expansion time. They receive unevaluated arguments
and produce new code to be evaluated.

@example
(defmacro when (condition . body)
  `(if ,condition (progn ,@@body)))

(when (> x 0)
  (print "positive")
  (print x))
;; Expands to: (if (> x 0) (progn (print "positive") (print x)))
@end example

Key points:
@itemize @bullet
@item Macro arguments are @strong{not} evaluated before the macro runs
@item The macro body produces a new expression (the @strong{expansion})
@item The expansion is then evaluated in the calling environment
@item Use quasiquote (@code{`}) with unquote (@code{,}) and splice (@code{,@@}) to build expansions
@end itemize

@node Tail Call Optimization
@chapter Tail Call Optimization

@cindex tail call optimization
@cindex TCO

T-Lisp optimizes recursive calls in tail position to use constant stack space.
A call is in tail position when it is the last thing a function does.

@example
;; Tail-recursive factorial
(defun factorial (n acc)
  (if (<= n 1)
      acc
      (factorial (- n 1) (* n acc))))

(defun fact (n)
  (factorial n 1))

(fact 100)  ; Works without stack overflow
@end example

The recursive call to @code{factorial} is in tail position because it is the
result of the @code{if} expression in the else branch.

